Yes! Pure virtual can have implementation:
```cpp
class Base {
public:
    virtual void process() = 0;  // Pure virtual
};

void Base::process() {  // Provide default
    std::cout << "Base default\n";
}

class Derived : public Base {
    void process() override {
        Base::process();  // Call base implementation
        std::cout << "Derived specific\n";
    }
};
```
Use cases:
- Provide default behavior derived classes can optionally call
- Shared initialization/cleanup code
- Template Method pattern

Class is still abstract despite implementation.

Default parameters are **statically bound** (compile-time), not polymorphic:
```cpp
class Base {
public:
    virtual void f(int x = 10) {
        std::cout << x << "\n";
    }
};

class Derived : public Base {
public:
    void f(int x = 20) override {
        std::cout << x << "\n";
    }
};

Base* ptr = new Derived();
ptr->f();  // Calls Derived::f but uses Base's default: prints 10!
```
**Critical rule**: Virtual dispatch is runtime, but default arguments are compile-time. Never rely on overridden default parameters. Better: avoid default parameters in virtual functions.

Delete copy operations, provide/default move operations:
```cpp
class MoveOnly {
    std::unique_ptr<Resource> resource;
public:
    MoveOnly() = default;

    // Delete copy
    MoveOnly(const MoveOnly&) = delete;
    MoveOnly& operator=(const MoveOnly&) = delete;

    // Allow move
    MoveOnly(MoveOnly&&) = default;
    MoveOnly& operator=(MoveOnly&&) = default;
};
```
Use cases:
- Unique ownership semantics (like `std::unique_ptr`)
- Non-copyable resources (file handles, sockets)
- Prevent expensive copies
- Enforce transfer of ownership

Move-only types work in containers and algorithms that support move semantics.

Explicitly delete destructor to prevent destruction:
```cpp
class HeapOnly {
    ~HeapOnly() = delete;  // Cannot destroy
public:
    static HeapOnly* create() {
        return new HeapOnly();
    }
    void destroy() {
        delete this;  // Only accessible from within class
    }
private:
    HeapOnly() = default;
};
```
Use cases:
- Enforce heap-only allocation
- Factory patterns with controlled lifetime
- Singleton patterns
- Memory pool management
- Objects that should never be stack-allocated

Alternative: private destructor (allows friends/members to destroy).

Copy elision can occur EVEN with deleted copy/move:
```cpp
class NoCopy {
public:
    NoCopy() = default;
    NoCopy(const NoCopy&) = delete;
};

NoCopy create() {
    return NoCopy();  // OK in C++17 - mandatory elision
}

NoCopy obj = create();  // OK - elision, no copy
```
Key points:
- **C++17**: Mandatory copy elision in certain cases (prvalue return)
- Elision **bypasses** the constructor entirely - no need for it to exist
- Pre-C++17: Elision is optional, so deleted copy would fail
- Compiler must verify copy/move is **possible** (not deleted) pre-C++17

This enables returning move-only types by value.

Destructors called in **reverse order** of construction:
```cpp
class Base {
public:
    ~Base() { cleanup(); }
    virtual void cleanup() { /* base cleanup */ }
};

class Derived : public Base {
    Resource* res;
public:
    ~Derived() {
        cleanup();  // Calls Base::cleanup!
        delete res;
    }
    void cleanup() override { /* derived cleanup */ }
};
```
Critical issues:
- During Derived destruction, **vptr already points to Base**
- Virtual calls in destructor resolve to Base version
- Derived parts already destroyed when Base destructor runs

**Solutions**:
- Don't call virtual functions in destructors
- Use explicit non-virtual cleanup methods
- Two-phase destruction pattern

Multiple techniques:

**1. Delete copy operations in base:**
```cpp
class Base {
protected:
    Base() = default;
    Base(const Base&) = delete;
    Base& operator=(const Base&) = delete;
public:
    virtual ~Base() = default;
};
```

**2. Make base abstract:**
```cpp
class Base {
public:
    virtual void interface() = 0;
    virtual ~Base() = default;
protected:
    Base() = default;
};
```

**3. Use std::enable_if for templates:**
```cpp
template<typename T>
void process(T& obj) {
    static_assert(std::is_base_of_v<Base, T>,
                  "Must pass by reference to polymorphic base");
}
```

Prevents accidental pass-by-value compilation.

Covariant return type pattern:
```cpp
class Base {
public:
    virtual Base* clone() const = 0;
    virtual ~Base() = default;
};

class Derived : public Base {
public:
    Derived* clone() const override {  // Covariant return
        return new Derived(*this);
    }

    // Ensure proper copy constructor
    Derived(const Derived&) = default;
};

// Usage
Base* original = new Derived();
Base* copy = original->clone();  // Polymorphic clone
delete original;
delete copy;
```
Benefits:
- Works polymorphically
- Type-safe (covariant return)
- Each derived class implements its own copy

Modern alternative: Return `std::unique_ptr` for automatic memory management.
